s which have a connection to the outside (like mouth, stomach, gut and so on) this is not really surprising that this is true for the bladder as well.<\/p>\n\n<p>Urine might be a relatively low risk solution of choice to rinse a wound when nothing else is available, but otherwise I wouldn't recommend it.<\/p>\n\n<p>Then think of what urine is used for: it is the way our body excretes all the water soluble stuff it doesn't need any more. The body makes a lot of effort here to concentrate the primary urine in our kidneys to recover all the stuff which is still needed and to save water. I wouldn't drink it and make my body go through the whole process of excretion again.<\/p>\n\n<p>About the doctors: is there any hard evidence for that or is this only an anecdote? I get highly skeptical when I hear about such stories.<\/p>\n","answer_id":17818,"question_id":17816,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1428185889}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/17816/does-urine-therapy-really-work","last_activity_date":1428185889,"creation_date":1401652907,"answer_count":1,"title":"Does urine therapy really work?","body":"<p>I heard a lecture from a supporter of urine therapy and he says that urine is not only good disinfection, but also drinkable source of minerals. I said to myself that I can take either one or the other, but not both at once. \nIn addition, the emphasis was on his own urine - and yet such example was given of a case of a boy who was hooked by jellyfish. The doctor, who was near him apparently saved using urine as an antiseptic. \nI myself heard but a very qualified doctor who administered this treatment. What do you think?<\/p>\n","question_id":17816,"tags":["excreta"],"score":7,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":105,"up_vote_count":7},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ae0014e2b5be5ac76e0892cdd6f72e8e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6289,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/