http://i.stack.imgur.com/YfqFK.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Source: <a href=\"https://www.qiagen.com/us/products/genes%20and%20pathways/pathway%20details/?pwid=44\">Qiagen<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/MoA9l.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/eTbpd.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Source: <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK21729/\">Molecular Cell Biology. 4th edition.<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Addendum: I said in my post that tRNA is charged in the cytoplasm, this is somewhat true. In mammalian cells, we also see that tRNA are charged in the nucleus as well, and it might aid in the export of some of these charged tRNAs. <a href=\"http://www.jbc.org/content/275/41/31559.full\">(Source)<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":31074,"question_id":31073,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1428182880}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31073/where-do-amino-acids-get-attached-to-trna-and-where-is-it-synthesized","last_activity_date":1428182880,"creation_date":1428177928,"answer_count":1,"title":"Where do amino acids get attached to tRNA and where is it synthesized?","body":"<p>Some very basic parts of transcription/translation seem to be left out in various literature. I can't find the answer to this anywhere:<\/p>\n\n<p>How exactly is tRNA synthesized? I realize that mRNA is synthesized through transcription and I know a lot about that. However tRNA is supposedly synthesized the same way but every time you read about transcription they just talk about how the mRNA then gets this and that...?<\/p>\n\n<p>Where do the amino acids get attached? Is it in the nucleus or outside the nucleus?<\/p>\n\n<p>Thanks.<\/p>\n","question_id":31073,"tags":["genetics","biochemistry","proteins","rna"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":31074,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":946,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/aioWT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15066,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15066/quality","reputation":197,"display_name":"Quality","accept_rate":80},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fcf9d3bdac2c3fa35177730c31b34f79?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6307/canadianer","reputation":6147,"display_name":"canadianer"},"score":1,"post_id":31075,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428182325,"comment_id":51879,"body":"<a href=\"http://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nucleation\" rel=\"nofollow\">en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nucleation<\/a>"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/dITzT.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14698,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14698/sleepses","reputation":532,"display_name":"Sleepses"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1428181631,"creation_date":1428181631,"body":"<p>In this context, i feel nucleated means being a \"core structure\", a substrate for the organization of one or multiple polymer chains.<\/p>\n","answer_id":31077,"question_id":31075,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12877/cmosychuk","reputation":4410,"display_name":"CMosychuk"},"score":5,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1428182273,"creation_date":1428182273,"body":"<p>Cytoskeletal nucleation refers to the <em>de novo<\/em> formation of cytoskeleton filaments. If microtubules are nucleating, that means microtubules are being polymerized from lit. \"From the beginning\" by α/ß-tubulin dimers. So literally, and we see in the image below, Arp2/3 complexes act as progenitor sites so to say for new actin filaments by the \"nucleation\" of actin:<\/p>\