ical process."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ZwVSN.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6576,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6576/paze","reputation":676,"display_name":"Paze","accept_rate":82},"score":0,"post_id":31046,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1428092829,"comment_id":51795,"body":"So why is phosphate a &quot;water soluble&quot; molecule but yet it stays as &quot;phosphate&quot; in water? It doesn&#39;t dissolve in water it stays phosphate?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":7591,"display_name":"MattDMo","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":31046,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428093085,"comment_id":51796,"body":"@BjarniJ&#243;hannsson see my answer below for an accessible explanation. If you are having trouble with the English words, you may want to look them up in your native language. You are confusing <i>dissolve<\/i> with <i>hydrolyze<\/i>."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Ohl3y.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":10143,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10143/jerepierre","reputation":345,"display_name":"jerepierre"},"score":2,"post_id":31046,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428093152,"comment_id":51797,"body":"You might be thinking of simple ionic compounds like sodium chloride, which when dissolved do separate into their constituent ions (e.g. sodium cation and chloride anion)."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r