ing on what parameter is being measured, but rest assured, paid professional athletes fall in the upper 1 percentile.<\/p>\n\n<p>Lets go back to intelligence for a moment. Take someone like Bobby Fischer (Chess Player), I.Q.: 187<\/p>\n\n<p>I guarantee you that <strong>even falling-down drunk, Bobby Fischer would have beaten me easily in a game of chess<\/strong> (and it's not because my I.Q. is average or below). It's because he was so very much, unimaginably better at chess than I am.<\/p>\n\n<p>I guarantee you that <strong>even falling-down drunk, Albert Einstein could solve mathematical equations I can't even write<\/strong>. It's because he was so very much, unimaginably more intelligent than I am.<\/p>\n\n<p>It's the same with great athletes. <em>Even if they drink every night, a great athlete will outperform you or me on any given day.<\/em><\/p>\n\n<p>That's why you are just dead wrong when you state \"<em>then it couldn't have been consumed by highest-ranking athletes, as alcohol-consuming athletes could never rich the heights of the tops of proffessional sports<\/em>\".<\/p>\n\n<p>You are just laboring under a completely false premise. These people are so much better than people only 1 percentile below them that drinking doesn't necessitate that they fall in the ranks. <\/p>\n","answer_id":31022,"question_id":30995,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1428024988}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/30995/alcohol-and-athletes","last_activity_date":1428024988,"creation_date":1427981357,"answer_count":1,"title":"Alcohol and athletes?","body":"<p>I've seen a lot of articles claiming that alcohol has a very bad impact on athletic performance. Examples include, but are by far not limited to: <\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://oade.nd.edu/educate-yourself-alcohol/alcohol-and-athletes/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://oade.nd.edu/educate-yourself-alcohol/alcohol-and-athletes/<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/the-running-blo