e current study are consistent with those of Fletcher and Jones (2004), and Young and Behm (2003) who determined that dynamic stretching elicits the best performance in power and high-speed activities <a href=\"http://digitalcommons.usu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1691&amp;context=etd\" rel=\"nofollow\">[1]<\/a>. <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>However, static stretching does not improve performance and can actually lead to injury.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The current study found static stretching to have a negative effect on agility, and acceleration (Fletcher &amp; Jones, 2004; Nelson et al., 2005). As acceleration is a component of agility, these findings support those of Fletcher and Jones (2004) and Nelson et al. (2005). Agility also involves components of braking, and change of direction. Static stretching prior to agility activities was found to have a negative effect on agility performance <a href=\"http://digitalcommons.usu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1691&amp;context=etd\" rel=\"nofollow\">[1]<\/a>. <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>To read up on dynamic and static stretching as well as other types of stretching, I would recommend MIT's <a href=\"http://web.mit.edu/tkd/stretch/stretching_4.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Types of Stretching<\/a> page.<\/p>\n\n<p>Additionally, the references to my reference one provides many more useful articles to look into.<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"http://digitalcommons.usu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1691&amp;context=etd\" rel=\"nofollow\">Static versus dynamic stretching effect on agility and performance<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","answer_id":30957,"question_id":30928,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1427941752}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/30928/does-taking-a-shower-have-the-same-effect-on-muscles-as-warming-up","last_activity_date":1427941752,"creation_date":1427779200,"answer_count":3,"title":"Does taking a shower have the same effect on muscles as warming up?","body":"<p>When playing sports, coaches and trainers are always very clear that it is necessary to warm up and stretch. But sometimes athletes sometimes want to get an extra stretch in and don't want to go through the hassle of warming up.<\/p>\n\n<p>Will taking a hot shower warm up muscles or does an athlete sctually have to do physical exercises like jogging in order to be ready to stretch? <\/p>\n\n<p>I know this sounds like a question I could go on the physical fitness SE, but I'm really hoping for an answer involving thermodynamics and I doubt I'll get that there. <\/p>\n","question_id":30928,"tags":["muscles"],"score":12,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":2023,"up_vote_count":12,"last_edit_date":1427808622},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1PZFP.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13359,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13359/learner","reputation":143,"display_name":"Learner"},"closed_date":1427941301,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":7591,"display_name":"MattDMo","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":30970,"edited":false,"creation_date":1427908105,"comment_id":51591,"body":"your link doesn&#39;t work..."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1PZFP.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13359,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13359/learner","reputation":143,"display_name":"Learner"},"score":0,"post_id":30970,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":7591,"display_name":"MattDMo","accept_rate":50},"edited":false,"creation_date":1427908192,"comment_id":51592,"body":"@MattDMo thanks I updated it and should work now"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2d50eaca20365c51634c9452835c50ab?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":14629,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14629/cactuswoman","reputation":1902,"display_name":"CactusWoman","accept_rate":60},"score":0,"post_id":30970,"edited":false,"creation_date":1427908321,"comment_id":51593,"body":"Your question is pretty broad. What specifically do you want to know about this pathway?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1PZFP.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13359,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13359/learner","reputation":143,"display_name":"Learner"},"score":0,"post_id":30970,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2d50eaca20365c51634c9452835c50ab?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":14629,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14629/cactuswoman","reputation":1902,"display_name":"CactusWoman","accept_rate":60},"edited":false,"creation_date":1427909023,"comment_id":51594,"body":"@CactusWoman my main question is how can we come to such conclusion that a pathway is very important or one is not! how to interpret such pathway shown in the link? and what can I understand from it? to be honest it is very complicated for me to understand it"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":30970,"edited":false,"creation_date":1427927426,"comment_id":51624,"body":"Please remove the link and make it a stand-alone question. I vote to close as unclear what you are asking."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchan