spx\">naming conventions<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Pf5bj.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Classification example (for <em>Homo sapiens<\/em>):<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/3e3Cr.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n","answer_id":17062,"question_id":17060,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1398973154}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/17060/what-is-the-proper-format-for-genus-and-species-names-in-latin","last_activity_date":1427877418,"creation_date":1398964156,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is the proper format for genus and species names in latin?","body":"<p>When using the latin nomenclature for a fish in printed materials (such as <em>Sander vitreus<\/em> for walleye), what is the correct capitalization of each word? <\/p>\n\n<p>In this example, should 'S' be uppercase only, or both 'S' and 'V' be upper/lower case?  <\/p>\n","question_id":17060,"tags":["taxonomy","nomenclature"],"score":6,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":10189,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1427877418},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/100002602028844/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":8226,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8226/user141670","reputation":21,"display_name":"user141670"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"score":1,"post_id":19492,"edited":false,"creation_date":1404561946,"comment_id":27815,"body":"Could you give us an indication of the size of the butterfly and the time of year you saw it?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/XDA2o.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":338,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/338/j-musser","reputation":1309,"display_name":"J. Musse