radiation may cause mutations in the DNA (<a href=\"http://www.pnas.org/content/82/24/8602.full.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">Gevertz et al, PNAS 1985<\/a>). Mutations, in turn, may lead to altered phenotypes. Altered phenotypes and survival of the fittest are key to evolution and formation of new species. <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>What is the (relative) contribution of background radiation on the formation of new species?<\/strong>. In other words, is background radiation a critical component in evolution and would the course of evolution have changed substantially when there would be no such background radiation?   <\/p>\n","question_id":30535,"tags":["evolution","natural-selection","molecular-evolution","radiation"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":453,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1426718738},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8f89a7c238c621dce4e357c45431bd9c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15170,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15170/keine","reputation":125,"display_name":"Keine"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ed56f1240fa17c09d0461c21679dd7dc?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15138,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15138/mimat","reputation":333,"display_name":"mimat"},"score":1,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8f89a7c238c621dce4e357c45431bd9c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15170,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15170/keine","reputation":125,"display_name":"Keine"},"score":0,"post_id":30935,"edited":false,"creation_date":1427798061,"comment_id":51509,"body":"Do you just use deionized water as the hypotonic media?. By the way, Dunaliella lacks a cell wall. Thanks for your answer!"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ed56f1240fa17c09d0461c21679dd7dc?s=128&d=identicon&r=P