s C<\/p>\n\n<p>example from literature, E.coli: fnr as A, and arcA as B, cydAB as C\nsource: <a href=\"http://www.pnas.org/content/100/21/11980.long\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.pnas.org/content/100/21/11980.long<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":30035,"question_id":27766,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/27766/is-it-possible-that-a-set-of-functionally-related-proteins-in-a-pathway-fulfill","last_activity_date":1427764543,"creation_date":1421483190,"answer_count":1,"title":"Is it possible that a set of functionally related proteins in a pathway fulfill different functions?","body":"<p>Could it be that a given pathway of enzymes (or proteins in general) may fulfill different purposes in a cell by for shifting partners? Say protein A activates B, B activates C and C has a specific action X (e.g. X = phosphorylation of protein D). Now do pathways exist where, e.g., A can activate C directly resulting in action Y (e.g. dephosphorylation of protein D)? <\/p>\n\n<p>At this time I am in need of real-world examples of this scenario, but I can't find any. Can anyone help? <\/p>\n","question_id":27766,"tags":["biochemistry","molecular-biology","proteins"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"unclear what you're asking","is_answered":false,"view_count":60,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1421507398},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/45ff880f37e76ded30235aa976e1c2df?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4497,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4497/flux","reputation":120,"display_name":"Flux","accept_rate":0},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6de2ee4a7f7e3323daea4eb795260f47?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1853,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1853/keegan-keplinger","reputation":688,"display_name":"Keegan Keplinger"},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.grava