 the water because their cornea has little to do with their vision."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":21936,"edited":false,"creation_date":1412830077,"comment_id":34862,"body":"Nice answer.. But the refractive index does have a role and the convexity of the lens as you rightly explained corrects for it. I had read about fish&#39;s highly convex lens but was not aware of diving animals having a flexible lens."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1412713791,"creation_date":1412713791,"body":"<p>It is more complicated than this, but... I don't think it has as much to do with the refractive index of water but rather the shape of our corneas and the loss of this shape advantage under water, for if the eyes are protected by goggles, one can see quite clearly underwater (much the same as a camera can, as the shape of it's lenses are not affected). Any change in the shape of the cornea changes the way light passes through the eye, and results in a change in vision. The following is from Ch. 9 Optics of the eyes of marine animals, from <a href=\"http://books.google.com/books?hl=en&amp;lr=&amp;id=nyc9AAAAIAAJ&amp;oi=fnd&amp;pg=PA149&amp;dq=corneal+shape+differences+and+vision+in+terrestrial+and+aquatic+animals&amp;ots=QqqBkWe7Bi&amp;sig=UK47BbHOtOCS-k4MNUAu-PTHZDw#v=onepage&amp;q=corneal%20shape%20differences%20and%20vision%20in%20terrestrial%20and%20aquatic%20animals&amp;f=false\" rel=\"nofollow\"><em>Light and Life in the Sea<\/em><\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/MQEhv.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>This is different for penguins (and turtles): the surface of their eyes, the cornea, is not as much vaulted as for humans (it's much flatter), and the lens is much rounder (meaning the shape can change more than our relatively flat lenses can), so the difference between air and water is not so big and the light isn't refracted too strongly. Also, the ciliary muscles (not to be confused with the pupillary muscles) holding the eye's lens (behind the pupil) are stronger, increasing their accommodation, so a penguin has a sharp sight in the water. Or as stated in <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-1-4684-3363-0_19\" rel=\"nofollow\">A Survey of Vertebrate Strategies for Vision in Air and Water<\/a><\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Whereas the cornea is usually the major refractive element of the terrestrial eye, it is of little or no refractive consequence to an aquatic vertebrate.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>See the difference in these four vertebrae groups (the first is man, the second is fish, the third is whales (similar to penguins) and the fourth is sirenians - manatees and dugongs)<sup><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/MQEhv.png\" rel=\"nofollow\">1<\/a><\/sup>:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/o9ekH.png\" alt=\"\"><\/p>\n\n<p><sub><a href=\"http://www.pinguins.info/Engels/BioKop_eng.html&lt;/sub&gt;\" rel=\"nofollow\">Penguins.info<\/a><br>\n[<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/MQEhv.png\" rel=\"nofollow\">1<\/a>] <a href=\"http://books.google.com/books?hl=en&amp;lr=&amp;id=dt0dhi5qB4YC&amp;oi=fnd&amp;pg=PA121&amp;dq=corneal+shape+differences+and+vision+in+terrestrial+and+aquatic+animals&amp;ots=pRarq6OpXz&amp;sig=TBMZ8vU7U7pnZ-2gF-H6AeEfveo#v=onepage&amp;q=corneal%20shape%20differences%20and%20vision%20in%20terrestrial%20and%20aquatic%20animals&amp;f=false\" rel=\"nofollow\">Comparative anatomy and physiology of vision in aquatic tetrapods<\/a><\/sub><\/p>\n","answer_id":21936,"question_id":21926,"up_vote_count":4}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/21926/how-do-animals-handle-light-refraction-in-different-media","last_activity_date":1427730432,"creation_date":1412683903,"answer_count":1,"title":"How do animals handle light refraction in different media?","body":"<p>For a human, when diving underwater, everything is blurry because of the water's different refractive index compared to that of air, which we are accustomed to. How do animals, like turtles, seals or penguins, handle that difference when changing the medium? Are they nearly blind at surface and can focus underwater or the other way around? Can they adapt to different refractive indexes on the fly? How?<\/p>\n","question_id":21926,"tags":["physiology","zoology","eyes"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":21936,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":287,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1412685414},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5a68f3fa9bf667a9cf38b357e45eb862?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":8618,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8618/paul-brewczynski","reputation":131,"display_name":"Paul Brewczynski"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/280c38f4cc343f0f3be19b35d2195c91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11736,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11736/jamesqf","reputation":401,"display_name":"jamesqf"},"score":3,"post_id":30852,"edited":false,"creation_date":1427562355,"comment_id":51306,"body":"Being a gardener with 50+ varieties of roses, from thornless &quot;Zephirine Drouhin&quot; on up, I think I&#39;m in a position to say that thorns of any sort do give a definite advantage - especially as I&#39;m in the middle of their spring pruning."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ada8eb98a784c579c00822290f13e70b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":8564,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8564/qubei","reputation":298,"display_name":"Qubei","accept_rate":60},"score":0,"post_id":30852,"edited":false,"creation_date":1427745342,"comment_id":51458,"body":"If you&#39;re looking for a trait which is maladapted to the natural environment then you should be looking at the rose&#39;s flower, Their flowers are a product of generations of selective breeding. Wild types have such simple flowers with so few petals they would hardly be recognised as roses. So I find it interesting that you pick out the thorns, which have such obvious utility, and would so even if they were tiny."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2d50eaca20365c51634c9452835c50ab?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":14629,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14629/cactuswoman","reputation":1902,"display_name":"CactusWoman","accept_rate":60},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/uTYSx.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14826,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14826/cagliari2005","reputation":2361,"display_name":"cagliari2005"},"score":2,"post_id":30854,"edited":false,"creation_date":1427561937,"comment_id":51303,"body":"Notably this answer about spikes is delivered by CactusWoman..."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2ad85f81981e5365a21d94114f3926b2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":11657,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11657/augurar","reputation":1124,"display_name":"augurar"},"score":0,"post_id":30854,"edited":false,"creation_date":1427610088,"comment_id":51352,"body":"I think it&#39;s generally believed that spines/thorns/prickles <i>are<\/i> adaptive in that they deter herbivory while still allowing for pollination.  But as Gould et al. rightly point out, this would need to be tested."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2d50eaca20365c51634c9452835c50ab?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":14629,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14629/cactuswoman","reputation":1902,"display_name":"CactusWoman","accept_rate":60},"score":0,"post_id":30854,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2ad85f81981e5365a21d94114f3926b2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":11657,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11657/augurar","reputation":1124,"display_name":"augurar"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1427679975,"comment_id":51411,"body":"@augurar Yes, it is well-known that spikes themselves deter herbivory. But the question was whether or not &quot;more spiky&quot; or more bulgy spikes were better than slimmer spikes."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1427560362,"creation_date":1427560362,"body":"<p>Just because you cannot forsee a use for more \"bulgy\" spikes doesn't mean there isn't a use for them. Furthermore, natural selection isn't about producing perfect organisms, it's about selecting for traits that are \"good enough\". There is also more to evolution than natural selection. The phenomenon of genetic drift can cause a neutral or slightly maladaptive trait to become fixed in the population.<\/p>\n\n<p>In short, not every single trait is adaptive. Check out the famous paper <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/77447?sid=21106272514503&amp;uid=2129&amp;uid=3739656&amp;uid=2&amp;uid=4&amp;uid=3739256&amp;uid=70\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Spandrels of San Marco<\/a> if you want to read more. It talks about how we shouldn't focus on trying to come up with an adaptionist theory for every trait and instead consider that other agents of evolutionary change, such as genetic drift, can generate non-adaptive traits.<\/p>\n","answer_id":30854,"question_id":30852,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":5,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1427730329,"creation_date":1427730329,"body":"<p>I think that the most important point has been given by CactusWoman, when (s)he says \"Just because you cannot forsee a use for more \"bulgy\" spikes doesn't mean there isn't a use for them.\"<\/p>\n\n<p>In addition to that, I would like to say that several plants evolved traits that were beneficial at a time where other herbivores existed and that are now useless. Those lineages did not lose their traits (yet?) just because there is a relatively low cost to making the trait in question.<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>Your post shows several of the very common misconception about evolutionary processes. Evolution is not all about Natural Selection. It is more interesting than that.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>\"small improvement\"<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The conception that evolution proceed through \"small improvements\" is either partially wrong or totally wrong.<\/p>\n\n<p>First, because of the loaded term \"improvement\". Evolution can yield a population to have a lower mean reproductive success or a lower complexity, things that you could eventually see as deterioration.<\/p>\n\n<p>Second, because changes not need to necessarily be small. Some mutations have a very big effect.<\/p>\n\n<p>Third, because even small deleterious mutations can spread in the population and reach fixation (=and all individuals carry this mutation), just because of the joint effect of other evolutionary processes such as genetic drift. This post may help you to get a quick grasp of what <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/14543/why-is-the-strength-of-genetic-drift-inversely-proportional-to-the-population-si\">genetic drift<\/a> is. There are already multiple posts that emphasize the importance of other processes than natural selection in evolution to layman. <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/21772/why-dont-mammals-have-more-than-4-limbs\">Here<\/a> is one of them.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>believe in Darwin competence<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Evolutionary biology is not anymore <code>Darwin's evolution theory<\/code>. It is way more than that. We've been working on the subject a lot since Darwin and today we have a much much better understanding of evolutionary processes than Darwin at its time. Everything is not fully understood yet and therefore there are still many people researching to better understand evolution. Of course, not to better test if evolution is true as this has been known for a long time now.<\/p>\n","answer_id":30911,"question_id":30852,"up_vote_count":5}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/30852/evolution-theory-roses-spikes-being-more-bulgy-doesnt-give-you-advantage","last_activity_date":1427730329,"creation_date":1427558701,"answer_count":2,"title":"Evolution theory - roses spikes - being more bulgy doesn't give you advantage","body":"<p>I've seen spike, huge spike. And I thought that development of such spikes could be contrary to the evolution theory. <\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/lQPXB.jpg\" alt=\"Spikes\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Being \u201elittle more\u201d spiky doesn\u2019t give you any advantage... So those individuals having one won't have smaller mortality rate than those with smooth stem. \nEven more, the individuals with bulgy (more spiky) waste resources their ruggedness and have more things to feed, which should mean that they would have higher mortality rate.<\/p>\n\n<p>So I can see no way to develop spikes on the stems of roses according to the evolution theory which embrace \"small improvement\". Spike is only efficient (to deter aggressor) when it's very sharp, it's either sharp or it isn't - there is little in between. <\/p>\n\n<p>Could anybody tell me that this is bullshit (and why it is bullshit), and that I should us believe in Darwin competence?;) <\/p>\n","question_id":30852,"tags":["evolution","botany","plant-anatomy"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":109,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/10205092727372304/picture?type=l