ckexchange.com/questions/29918/why-do-most-organisms-have-negative-supercoiled-dna/30420#30420\">post<\/a> has more information about DNA helical tension. Also note that exceptions exist (i.e. right-ended direction) especially for histone at the centromere as described in this <a href=\"http://jcb.rupress.org/content/186/4/453.full#ref-16\" rel=\"nofollow\">paper<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>For your second question, the exact way nucleosomes are then arranged to produce the chromatin fiber is, as far as I know, still not fully understood but the most accepted model is a zigzag arrangement (<a href=\"http://cshperspectives.cshlp.org/content/2/5/a000596.full.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Woodcock CL &amp; Ghosh RP, 2010<\/a> and <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22394510\" rel=\"nofollow\">Grigoryev SA &amp; Woodcock CL<\/a>).<\/p>\n","answer_id":30899,"question_id":23664,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/23664/nucleosome-wrapping-direction","last_activity_date":1427687650,"creation_date":1415004364,"answer_count":1,"title":"Nucleosome wrapping direction","body":"<p>Does anyone know which direction the nucleosomes are wrapped? I wonder:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Relative to the B-DNA double helix twist direction (right-hand)<\/li>\n<li>Relative to the neighbor nucleosomes. Do they alternate to prevent supercoiling?<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","question_id":23664,"tags":["dna","nucleic-acids","structure-prediction","histone"],"score":6,"accepted_answer_id":30899,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":72,"up_vote_count":6},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d4821e986f388b833f0f5946132c4d9b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13127,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13127/user170231","reputation":196,"display_name":"user170231","accept_rate":71},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/uTYSx.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14826,"link":"h