 using them for regenerative medicine, drug discovery, etc. <\/p>\n\n<p>Recently there were several articles published in nature:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v516/n7530/full/516172a.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Stem cells: A designer's guide to pluripotency<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v516/n7530/full/nature14046.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Genome-wide characterization of the routes to pluripotency<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>amongst others. Also you can check out <a href=\"http://www.stemformatics.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.stemformatics.org/<\/a> for more information on stem cells and research being done. <\/p>\n","answer_id":30874,"question_id":30871,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1427623584}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/30871/what-are-ipsc-cells-and-what-are-their-applications","last_activity_date":1427623584,"creation_date":1427613230,"answer_count":1,"title":"What are iPSC cells, and what are their applications?","body":"<p>I also searched it on internet, and just basically know it's related to the Stem Cells, but there are too many resources, can anyone help me find out more about them, like their applications? They really interest me.   <\/p>\n","question_id":30871,"tags":["cell-biology","cell","stem-cells"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":1,"closed_reason":"too broad","is_answered":true,"view_count":91,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1427623368},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e997212da55bf03f7bcc0e3be68d3c14?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":15116,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15116/jerry","reputation":6,"display_name":"jerry"},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/30782/location-of-embryo-development-in-angiosperms","last_activity_date":1427614805,"creation_date":1427332421,"answer_count":0,"title":"Location of embryo development in angiosperms","body":"<p>What floral organ does the development of the embryos of angiosperms occurs in? Is it the ovary? The pollen tube grows down through the style and double fertilization occurs and the embryo begins to develop in the megasporangium.<\/p>\n","question_id":30782,"tags":["botany","reproduction","plant-anatomy"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":31,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1427614805},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f524f51edb2e0e559de5f027217b2d47?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14815,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14815/ro-siv","reputation":535,"display_name":"Ro Siv","accept_rate":97},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fcf9d3bdac2c3fa35177730c31b34f79?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6307/canadianer","reputation":6147,"display_name":"canadianer"},"score":1,"post_id":30817,"edited":false,"creation_date":1427614612,"comment_id":51360,"body":"Your second to last paragraph is worded wrong. Deleterious mutations are negatively selected against."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/uTYSx.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14826,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14826/cagliari2005","reputation":2361,"display_name":"cagliari2005"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1427608751,"creation_date":1427607199,"body":"<p>Lets assume for simplicity that DNA is globally subjected to the same mutation rate (which is probably not a fully correct assumption).<\/p>\n\n<p>Now let take a DNA region which is functional (what you meant by giving a fitness benefit), mutations in this region will occur as anywhere else in the genome. Some mutations will be deleterious and reduce the fitness of (or kill) the cell therefore, on the long run, cells that do not carry those deleterious mutations will propagate. This means that now if you look at the genome in the cell that propagated, certain genomic regions will contain less mutations than other because of the negative selection. They were \"protected\" against deleterious mutation.<\/p>\n\n<p>Similarly, In multicellular organisms any mutations that reduces the fitness of the germline cells will be negatively selected (again functional regions will be more conserved).<\/p>\n\n<p>The author was likely referring to regulatory regions. These are regions that do not encode proteins but are very important for gene regulations. Regulatory regions include enhancers, silencers, insulators and locus control regions (<a href=\"http://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev.genom.7.080505.115623?url_ver=Z39.88-2003&amp;rfr_dat=cr_pub%3Dpubmed&amp;rfr_id=ori%3Arid%3Acrossref.org&amp;journalCode=genom\" rel=\"nofollow\">Maston GA, 2006<\/a>). These regions will also be more conserved as deleterious mutations in regulatory elements could reduce the fitness of the cell/germline.<\/p>\n","answer_id":30869,"question_id":30817,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1427608751}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/30817/understanding-conclusions-that-functional-regions-are-under-negative-selection","last_activity_date":1427614801,"creation_date":1427416158,"answer_count":1,"title":"Understanding conclusions that functional regions are under negative selection?","body":"<p>I am reading in notes for a comparative annotation lecture that :<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>all DNA is subject to mutations<\/li>\n<li>most functional regions are under negative selection (ie., mutations are often deleterious)<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>The conclusion was: <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>that pieces of DNA with specific functions (especially genes) tend to be conserved against mutation more strongly than a DNA region with no specific function.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>So if i understand it properly, since all DNA can accumulate mutations, the regions of genes that provide some fitness benefits avoid the negative selection of random mutations and are preserved (conserved?).<\/p>\n\n<p>Also, the author placed in parentheses, (especially genes), therefore are there non coding regions that can provide benefits? Is he referring to \"Selfish DNA\" like Transposable elements that can have regulatory functions (or so i have heard).<\/p>\n","question_id":30817,"tags":["genetics","genomics","mutations"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":30869,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":47,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1427614801},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Ubbmd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5729,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5729/katherinebridges","reputation":372,"display_name":"katherinebridges","accept_rate":94},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Ic4na.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14735,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14735/nandor-poka","reputation":2578,"display_name":"Nandor Poka","accept_rate":75},"score":2,"post_id":30702,"edited":false,"creation_date":1427140835,"comment_id":50914,"body":"most likely they kill these bacteria after the product is made and / or use preservatives."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d7c5cbd0c2f965a3712ff687c53f997?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14552,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14552/aaaaaa","reputation":2058,"display_name":"aaaaaa"},"score":0,"post_id":30702,"edited":false,"creation_date":1427147574,"comment_id":50920,"body":"high-energy X-rays might help kill a lot of bacteria. But you need to control dose not to overheat sample"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b10de963b115fd0720d6a558fd1ac06c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10456/march-ho","reputation":5867,"display_n