>\n<li>100% oxygen is toxic to the lungs, as it is to many other things as well.  <\/li>\n<li>How would the oxygen diffuse to all the other areas of the lung that need oxygen? Diffusion is a complicated process in a structure like the lungs.<\/li>\n<li>from what would it produce oxygen? For example, would it extract it from water? How would the body deal with the loss of moisture from the air in out lungs? Where would the excess hydrogen go?<\/li>\n<li>Hydrogen is highly flammable around 29%. Would we become fire-breathing?<\/li>\n<li>How would the machine not hyperinflate and thus injure the lung?  <\/li>\n<li>How would we get rid of CO<sub>2<\/sub>? We would still have to breathe in and out.<\/li>\n<li>Etc.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","answer_id":30848,"question_id":30844,"up_vote_count":4}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/30844/what-would-happen-if-we-had-a-device-that-produced-oxygen-inside-of-our-lungs","last_activity_date":1427529257,"creation_date":1427505104,"answer_count":1,"title":"What would happen if we had a device that produced oxygen inside of our lungs?","body":"<p>Hypothetically speaking, suppose there is a device that produces a limitless supply of oxygen. The device is inhaled by a human and is resting inside the (a) lung.<\/p>\n\n<p>What would hypothetically happen if this were possible? <\/p>\n","question_id":30844,"tags":["human-biology","breathing","human-physiology"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":2,"closed_reason":"primarily opinion-based","is_answered":true,"view_count":62,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1427513287},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31bb21aa993c2dc03b65f1faf3e29151?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15131,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15131/bobhob314","reputation":6,"display_name":"bobhob314"},"closed_date":1427614707,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fcf9d3bdac2c3fa35177730c31b34f79?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6307/canadianer","reputation":6147,"display_name":"canadianer"},"score":1,"post_id":30818,"edited":false,"creation_date":1427442227,"comment_id":51217,"body":"What do you mean by &quot;if the alleles B/b and G/g were on the same chromosome&quot;? Are you saying that the parental genotype is BG/bg? Chromosomes are inherited as a unit. Without crossing over, if the parental genotype is BG/bg, only either BG or bg can be passed on. This means the offspring could be BG/BG, BG/bg or bg/bg."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31bb21aa993c2dc03b65f1faf3e29151?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15131,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15131/bobhob314","reputation":6,"display_name":"bobhob314"},"score":0,"post_id":30818,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fcf9d3bdac2c3fa35177730c31b34f79?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6307/canadianer","reputation":6147,"display_name":"canadianer"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1427569219,"comment_id":51310,"body":"No, I mean that allele1 that encodes for B or b and allele2 that encodes for G or g are on the same chromosome. Thanks!"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fcf9d3bdac2c3fa35177730c31b34f79?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6307/canadianer","reputation":6147,"display_name":"canadianer"},"score":0,"post_id":30818,"edited":false,"creation_date":1427573146,"comment_id":51314,"body":"I think you have the wrong terminology. You,re saying that the genes which encode for B or b and G or g are on the same chromosome. This is the situation I described in my first comment. The answer to your question depends on what the parental genotypes are."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gra